 2015 Iran nuclear deal or Syria's declared renunciation and actual use of its chemical weapons, influence their architecture? The Politics of Weapons Inspections examines the successes, failures, and lessons that can be learned from WMD monitoring and verification regimes in order to help determine how best to maintain and strengthen these regimes in the future. In addition to examining these regimes' technological, political, and legal contexts, Nathan E. Busch and Joseph F. Pilat reevaluate the track record of monitoring and verification in the historical cases of South Africa, Libya, and Iraq; assess the prospects of using these mechanisms in verifying arms control and disarmament; and apply the lessons learned from these cases to contemporary controversies over suspected or confirmed programs in North Korea, Iran, and Syria. Finally, they provide a forward-looking set of policy recommendations for the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aBiological arms controlxVerification. 0aChemical arms controlxVerification. 0aDisarmamentxOn-site inspection. 0aNuclear arms controlxVerification. 0aWeapons of mass destruction. 4aIAEA. 4aIran Nuclear Deal. 4aIran. 4aLibya. 4aNorth Korea. 4aNuclear weapons. 4aOPCW. 4aSouth Africa. 4aSyria. 4aWeapons of Mass Destruction. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aPilat, Joseph F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360162840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503601628423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503601628.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles